GCD curves of NiCo-LDH@CNT, (NC)VO@CNT, and (NC)VO/NGQD@CNT at current densities of 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, and 10 A g−1 are displayed in Fig. 4d and Fig. S3c-d. These curves exhibit good symmetry across various current densities, indicating nearly identical charging and discharging times. This symmetry demonstrates high reversibility of the electrode materials. Additionally, the extended voltage plateau provides strong evidence of Faraday reactions occurring within the electrodes. Fig. 4e illustrates the specific capacity of each electrode material, derived from the respective GCD curves. The (NC)VO/NGQD@CNT composite achieves a remarkable specific capacity of 3018.2 F g−1 at a current density of 1 A g−1. As the current density increases, the capacity gradually decreases, reaching 2332 F g−1 at 10 A g−1, with a capacity retention rate of 77.3 %. For comparison, the specific capacity of NiCo-LDH@CNT and (NC)VO@CNT are detailed in Table S1. Electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) was used to analyze the internal resistance pertaining to charge transfer and storage mechanisms within the electrode. Typically, an EIS plot comprises a semicircle arc in the high-frequency domain and a diagonal line segment in the low-frequency regime. In the high-frequency region, the intercept at the X-axis represents the equivalent series resistance (Rs
                     ), with a smaller intercept indicating a lower Ohmic impedance of the solution species. Moreover, the diameter of a semicircle in the high-frequency region represents the charge transfer resistance (Rct
                     ). A smaller diameter indicates lower charge transfer resistance and faster charge transfer speed within the system. As for the low-frequency region, the slope of the diagonal line determines the Warburg impedance, and a steeper slope signifies a more efficient charge transfer rate between the electrolyte and electrode, leading to lower impedance [11]. The EIS data are presented in Fig. 4f along with the equivalent circuit diagram, which includes Rs
                     , Rct
                     , and Warburg impedance components. From the EIS curves, it is evident that (NC)VO/NGQD@CNT composite has the smallest intercept and semicircle diameter on the X-axis (detailed fitted data are shown in Table S2), which unequivocally points to the lowest equivalent series resistance and charge transfer resistance. In addition, the straight line in the low-frequency region has the steepest slope, indicating the lowest electrolyte diffusion resistance. These collective findings collectively indicate that the (NC)VO/NGQD@CNT composite has high conductivity and faster charge transfer kinetics, making it a highly efficient electrode material.
